Title: THE FOUR OLDS
Credit: sc03 v5 — the simulator is furniture; the case is the scene
Draft date: 2026-07-12 19:13

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

A pull-cord CLICKS, and a bare bulb comes up over the APOLLO PROCEDURES TRAINER that fills half the barn.

The other half holds a card table and folding chairs, with a percolator working on a hot plate. The back wall carries the logbooks, spines dated from 1972.

The trainer hums under the whole room, low and constant.

HEADLIGHTS rake across the logbook wall. Three trucks come up the drive nose to tail and stop where they always stop.

GUNNY TIBBS, 71, in a Navy ball cap, gets to the door first and props it open with his boot.

GUNNY:
Dutch. You're late by my watch.

DUTCH HAAS, 76, thin, a canvas ledger under one arm, crosses the yard without hurrying.

DUTCH:
Your watch runs two minutes fast. It has since April.

STITCH McGREW, 74, ambles in behind him, coat open, in no hurry about any of it.

STITCH:
Evening, Gunny. Evening, Dutch.

Inside, CRICKET DAWES, 79, stands at the percolator with his back to the door. It's already going, already loud.

Gunny stops in the doorway and looks at the cot folded up in the corner, then at the coffee.

GUNNY:
You slept out here again.

CRICKET:
Percolator's about done. Cups are by the sink.

Gunny sets his cap square, takes a clipboard off its nail, and comes to attention.

GUNNY:
Apollo Eighteen. Lunar descent rehearsal. Number two thousand, eight hundred and six.

Nobody laughs. Stitch pours himself a cup. Dutch opens the ledger flat on the table and smooths the page.

STITCH:
Well. Got a motion on the floor. That landing they threw the parade for, out of Houston.

GUNNY:
We're not in session yet.

STITCH:
(to Gunny)
We're in session. I'm prosecuting.
(then)
Computer flew the whole thing top to bottom. Fella never laid a hand on it. Came in long, good half mile, maybe better, and they've got him on a float down Main Street with a band behind him.

DUTCH:
(reading)
Four hundred yards. I wrote it down Thursday, the ninth, off the television.

STITCH:
Four hundred yards is what the network will own up to.

GUNNY:
You can't enter what they won't even show. That's not evidence.

STITCH:
(to Gunny)
Rule of the barn. Whatever the computer did, the pilot didn't. Been on the books since '73.

GUNNY:
There's no such damn rule.

STITCH:
There is now.

DUTCH:
The machine flew it inside its own limits. That part's on the record too.

STITCH:
Then he didn't fly anything. He just sat there.

They all look at Cricket. He tops off his cup and keeps his back to them.

CRICKET:
Machine landed it. He rode it down.

Stitch points a finger at Cricket, satisfied, and turns back to the table.

STITCH:
That's the finding. Now the verdict.
(then)
Any one of us, thirty years back, puts it down by hand, right on the line.

GUNNY:
The unit concurs.

DUTCH:
For the record, my figure stands.

STITCH:
(to Dutch)
So noted. How do you vote.

DUTCH:
Guilty. Not one of those boys would have cleared our physical.

Cricket sips his coffee and says nothing. Gunny marks it down as unanimous.

Gunny hangs the clipboard back on its nail and squares his cap a last time.

GUNNY:
Net closed. Same time Tuesday.

CRICKET:
God willing.

Engines turn over in the yard. Taillights pull down the drive, one, then the next, then the last.

Cricket runs a padlock through the door hasp and pulls it once to check it.

Past the yard the farmhouse stands dark, no light in any window.
